'''Candi''' chhai [[Yin-nì-ngî]] he hìn-yùng yit-chho ló-kú ke [[kiûng-meu]], chhai [[Yin-thu-fu̍t-kau Sṳ̀-thoi]] pûn ngìn kien-li̍p ke.<ref name="Candi Sewu">Jacques Dumarçay, "Candi Sewu: dan arsitektur bangunan agama buda di Jawa Tengah : and buddhist architecture of Central Java", Kepustakaan Populer Gramedia, 2007, 9799100887, 9789799100887.</ref> Sin-thù sṳ́-yung yá-teû kien-chuk lòi chhùng-pai [[Fu̍t]] ya-he [[Yin-thu-kau]] ke [[sṳ̀n-mìn]]. Candi, yá-chak ki-fa m̀-tân-chhiang pâu-hàm meu ke yi-sṳ, me cho-tet hìn-yùng phe̍t-ke ló-kú Yin-thu-fu̍t-kau Sṳ̀-thoi ke kien-chuk pí-lun-kóng [[kiûng-thien]] (''kraton''), [[yo̍k-thòng]] (''petirtaan''), [[sàng-mùn]] (''gapura'') tén-tén. 

Yin-thu-kau siông-sin sṳ̀n-mìn he tai chhai Mahameru-sân tú, ku-só candi chhiu-he Mahameru-sân fu̍k-chṳ-phín ke kien-chuk. 

Jawa, Bali, Sumatera, Kalimantan-tó mân-nài tu-yû candi. M̀-ko chui-tô ke só-chhai chhiu-he Chûng-Jawa lâu Tûng-Jawa.  

